{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628423"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17216"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17216"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.77,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70422"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9906"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2977"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70422"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe diffuse headache. The headache is pulsating in nature and worsens with physical activity. He has associated chest pain and has not passed urine for eight hours. He has a history of poorly controlled hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include Metformin and Amlodipine, though he admits to poor compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and confused. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 220/130 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Fundoscopy reveals flame haemorrhages and papilloedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal arteritis","Intracranial neoplasm","Hypertensive crisis","Bacterial meningitis","Intracranial hypotension"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical features of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertensive crisis\u003C/strong\u003E and hypertensive encephalopathy. Severely elevated blood pressure, altered mental status, and end-organ damage (retinopathy and oliguria) strongly supports this diagnosis. It requires immediate intervention to prevent further organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older adults and presents with temporal headache, scalp tenderness, and jaw claudication. While it can cause elevated blood pressure, it would not explain this degree of hypertension or the associated end-organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracranial neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes progressive headache over weeks to months, often worse in the morning or with lying flat. While it can cause altered mental status, it would not explain the acute presentation with systemic involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with fever, neck stiffness, and photophobia. The presence of severe hypertension and end-organ damage make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracranial hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes positional headache that improves with lying flat and worsens with upright posture. It would not explain the severe hypertension or systemic manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertensive crisis typically presents with severe headache, altered mental status, and end-organ damage including cardiac and/or renal manifestations.","The presence of oliguria suggests acute kidney injury, which is a common complication of malignant hypertension.","Diffuse, pulsating headache with systemic symptoms requires urgent evaluation for life-threatening causes."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Alley WD, Schick MA. Hypertensive Emergency. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470371/","Rodriguez MA, Kumar SK, De Caro M. Hypertensive crisis. Cardiol Rev. 2010 Mar-Apr;18(2):102-7. doi: 10.1097/CRD.0b013e3181c307b7. PMID: 20160537."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17216"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T08:59:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T19:05:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9906"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":